casts.text:
One fascinating thing about the @0xprivacypools approach to privacy is that it actually is fully compatible with policing insider trading of this type, even if trading is anonymous (!!)

The basic idea is that ASPs would be able to blacklist the coins that came out of the trade, and so anyone who wants access to the largest anonymity sets would have to prove that their coins came from somewhere other than that trade. The trader themselves would not be able to make such a proof, and so they would only be able to mix with others that use an allow-everyone anonymity set. This would be a much smaller set, and it seems to me quite likely that it would be able to handle thousands and maybe hundreds of thousands of dollars if you're careful, but definitely not $88 million.

For lawyers, you can think of this as an "in rem" ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In_rem_jurisdiction ) approach to dealing with the problem: instead of starting from the question "who did it?", start from the question "which are the coins that are connected to the problem?" Thanks to the magic of ZK, you can boycott coins without even needing to know anything about the people who control them.

Furthermore, if defi protocols are adding more privacy, it seems likely in their interest to include such a mechanism. For a market maker, your primary cost is "toxic order flow": orders from sellers that are exploiting you because they have an information advantage. And so as a platform, you want to make things harder for insider traders.

https://x.com/Vivek4real_/status/1976787212491801051

cast.text:
A Friday thread that you provably won‚Äôt see from anyone else, starting with
a birthday message from Pavel, founder of @telegram üßµ:

‚ÄúI‚Äôm turning 41, but I don‚Äôt feel like celebrating.

Our generation is running out of time to save the free Internet built for us by our fathers.

What was once the promise of the free exchange of information is being turned into the ultimate tool of control.

Once-free countries are introducing dystopian measures such as digital IDs (UK), online age checks (Australia), and mass scanning of private messages (EU).

Germany is persecuting anyone who dares to criticize officials on the Internet. The UK is imprisoning thousands for their tweets. France is criminally investigating tech leaders who defend freedom and privacy.

A dark, dystopian world is approaching fast ‚Äî while we‚Äôre asleep. Our generation risks going down in history as the last one that had freedoms ‚Äî and allowed them to be taken away.

We‚Äôve been fed a lie.

We‚Äôve been made to believe that the greatest fight of our generation is to destroy everything our forefathers left us: tradition, privacy, sovereignty, the free market, and free speech.

By betraying the legacy of our ancestors, we‚Äôve set ourselves on a path toward self-destruction ‚Äî moral, intellectual, economic, and ultimately biological.

So no, I‚Äôm not going to celebrate today. I‚Äôm running out of time. We are running out of time.‚Äù

casts.text:
@alok says ‚Äú3 out of 20‚Äù people in crypto are currently aware of apptokens. he thinks more will be soon.

apptokens are "creator" constrained tokens, like ERC-721C & ERC-20C.
driven purely by developer demand, ‚Äúthe majority of new NFTs across @ethereum are 721Cs.‚Äù

built by Limit Break and @gabrielleydon (one of the best game designers in the world), apptokens are already powering new experiences on @opensea and Ronin.

the possibilities are built for gaming, and also go beyond.

some include 1) royalty enforcing-tokens, 2) spend-only tokens, 3) token trading restrictions (to specific pairs, price ranges, or whitelists), 4) custom vesting, expiries, or seasonal windows, and 5) "backed tokens", with guaranteed redemption logic.

these are just some examples of the constraints that you can place on apptokens (+ the programmable AMM built to service them).

casts.text:
I‚Äôve worked in the socials world since 2008, here‚Äôs what I‚Äôve learned, and patterns I‚Äôve collected, by the decade:

2000s: Social was raw. We were all just experimenting with how people connect online. I built one of the first social discovery products before there was a newsfeed or timeline. It blew up fast, 6M users in months, because the novelty was insane. Back then, you could scale just by being first.

2010s: This was the ‚Äúscale and kill‚Äù decade. I built Fab, which went from zero to $120M revenue in 18 months. For a while we felt invincible. Then Amazon showed up and crushed us. Lesson: if you‚Äôre just curating, you‚Äôll get eaten alive. The only moat is community + brand. Which is still true to this day.

2020s: Anyone can ship an app now. The real moat is community, can you create a space that feels alive, where people actually win together? That‚Äôs why we‚Äôve bet everything on Senpi. We‚Äôre building the first AI-powered wallet that doesn‚Äôt just hold your assets, it thinks and trades with you. It learns, adapts, and helps users actually beat the market.

If the 2000s were about novelty, and the 2010s were about scale, the 2020s are about intelligent products + community flywheels. Senpi lives right at that intersection.

After almost two decades in social, I‚Äôve learnt that novelty gets you attention, scale pressure-tests your moat and community is the only thing that endures the test of time.
